404. The dependence of one noun upon another is usually expressed by the genitive. As a rule this relationship should not be expressed in Latin by a preposition‚ thus making the preposi- tion a sort of conjunction between the two nounS. Such forms of expression are common enough in English, but in Latin the genitive or some other construction is preferred. For example, we say the war against the Gauls,· the Romans would say Bellum Gallbrum or Bellum Gallicum or Bellum in Gallbs gestum.
